-- Chilean Stocks: Colbun and Gener Gain; Falabella and Ripley Fall
-- B y   E d u a r d o   T h o m s o n
-- 2011-12-27T20:53:39Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-27/chilean-stocks-colbun-gains-falabella-and-ripley-retreat.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in Chilean trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the close in Santiago.  The  Ipsa (IPSA)  index rose 0.3 percent to 4,187.93. The  MSCI Chile (MXCL) 
index was little changed at 2,260.28.  AES Gener SA (GENER)   rose 1.2 percent to 276.35 pesos,
ending a four day losing streak. Chile’s second-largest power
generator expects to sign electricity contracts with Chilean
mining companies in the first half of next year as the top
copper-producing nation expands output of the metal, Chief
Executive Officer Felipe Ceron said in an interview.  Colbun SA (COLBUN)   gained 1.1 percent to 129.99 pesos,
with trading volume of almost nine times the average of the last
three months. Chile’s third-largest power generator by installed
capacity said in a regulatory filing yesterday that it reached
an agreement with natural gas transporter Gasoducto Gasandes SA
to annul contracts in Argentina and Chile, which will result in
savings of $19.2 million between 2012 and 2022 and $9.6 million
between 2023 and 2028.  The company also announced today it received $94.1 million
from a consortium of building companies for contractual non-
compliance.  Ripley Corp SA (RIPLEY)  , Chile’s third-largest
department store operator, fell 0.4 percent to 483.1 pesos, its
third day of losses. Chile’s Chamber of Commerce cut its
forecast for retail sale growth in 2011 to 9 percent from 10
percent, according to a statement e-mailed yesterday.  SACI Falabella (FALAB)   retreated 0.5 percent to 4,128.8
pesos, its third day of losses. Chile’s largest retailer by
market value is considering listing American depositary receipts
in 2012, Diario Financiero wrote.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Eduardo Thomson in Santiago at 
